      "content": "Azure infrastructure services implementation guidelines",
      "pos": [
        27,
        82
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Learn about the key design and implementation guidelines for deploying an IT workload in Azure infrastructure services.",
      "pos": [
        101,
        220
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure infrastructure services implementation guidelines",
      "pos": [
        604,
        659
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure is an excellent platform to implement dev/test or proof-of-concept configurations, because it requires very little investment to test a particular approach to an implementation of your solutions.",
      "pos": [
        661,
        862
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, you must be able to distinguish the easy practices for a dev/test environment from the more difficult, detailed practices for a fully functional, production-ready implementation of an IT workload.",
      "pos": [
        863,
        1068
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This guidance identifies many areas for which planning is vital to the success of an IT workload in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        1070,
        1176
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, planning provides an order to the creation of the necessary resources.",
      "pos": [
        1177,
        1260
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Although there is some flexibility, we recommend that you apply the order in this article to your planning and decision-making.",
      "pos": [
        1261,
        1388
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article was adapted from the content in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure implementation guidelines<ept id=\"p1\">](http://blogs.msdn.com/b/thecolorofazure/archive/2014/05/13/azure-implementation-guidelines.aspx)</ept> blog post.",
      "pos": [
        1390,
        1580
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Thanks to Santiago Cánepa (Application Development Manager for Microsoft) and Hugo Salcedo (Application Development Manager for Microsoft) for their original material.",
      "pos": [
        1581,
        1748
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Affinity groups have been deprecated.",
      "pos": [
        1752,
        1802
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Their use is not described here.",
      "pos": [
        1803,
        1835
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>About regional VNets and affinity groups<ept id=\"p1\">](../virtual-network/virtual-networks-migrate-to-regional-vnet.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1836,
        1970
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "1. Naming conventions",
      "pos": [
        1975,
        1996
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should have a good naming convention in place before creating anything in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        1998,
        2082
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A naming convention ensures that all the resources have a predictable name, which helps lower the administrative burden associated with managing those resources.",
      "pos": [
        2083,
        2244
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You might choose to follow a specific set of naming conventions defined for your entire organization or for a specific Azure subscription or account.",
      "pos": [
        2246,
        2395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Although it is easy for individuals within organizations to establish implicit rules when working with Azure resources, when a team needs to work on a project on Azure, that model does not scale well.",
      "pos": [
        2396,
        2596
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should agree on a set of naming conventions up front.",
      "pos": [
        2598,
        2655
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are some considerations regarding naming conventions that cut across the sets of rules that make up those conventions.",
      "pos": [
        2656,
        2780
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Affixes",
      "pos": [
        2786,
        2793
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When creating certain resources, Azure uses some defaults to simplify management of the resources that are associated with these resources.",
      "pos": [
        2795,
        2934
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, when creating the first virtual machine for a new cloud service, the Azure portal attempts to use the virtual machine’s name for the name of a new cloud service for the virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        2935,
        3133
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Therefore, it is beneficial to identify types of resources that need an affix to identify that type.",
      "pos": [
        3135,
        3235
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, clearly specify whether the affix will be at:",
      "pos": [
        3236,
        3294
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The beginning of the name (prefix)",
      "pos": [
        3298,
        3332
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The end of the name (suffix)",
      "pos": [
        3335,
        3363
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For instance, here are two possible names for a resource group that hosts a calculation engine:",
      "pos": [
        3365,
        3460
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Rg-CalculationEngine (prefix)",
      "pos": [
        3464,
        3493
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "CalculationEngine-Rg (suffix)",
      "pos": [
        3496,
        3525
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Affixes can refer to different aspects that describe the particular resources.",
      "pos": [
        3527,
        3605
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following table shows some examples typically used.",
      "pos": [
        3606,
        3661
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Aspect",
      "pos": [
        3663,
        3669
      ]
    },
