      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "01, 02, 03, etc.",
      "pos": [
        4174,
        4190
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For resources that have more than one instance.",
      "pos": [
        4193,
        4240
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, load balanced web servers in a cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        4241,
        4299
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When establishing your naming conventions, make sure that they clearly state which affixes to use for each type of resource, and in which position (prefix vs suffix).",
      "pos": [
        4301,
        4467
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Dates",
      "pos": [
        4473,
        4478
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is often important to determine the date of creation from the name of a resource.",
      "pos": [
        4480,
        4564
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We recommend the YYYYMMDD date format.",
      "pos": [
        4565,
        4603
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This format ensures that not only the full date is recorded, but also that two resources whose names differ only on the date will be sorted alphabetically and chronologically at the same time.",
      "pos": [
        4604,
        4796
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Naming resources",
      "pos": [
        4802,
        4818
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should define each type of resource in the naming convention, which should have rules that define how to assign names to each resource that is created.",
      "pos": [
        4820,
        4975
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These rules should apply to all types of resources, for example:",
      "pos": [
        4976,
        5040
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Subscriptions",
      "pos": [
        5044,
        5057
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Accounts",
      "pos": [
        5060,
        5068
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage accounts",
      "pos": [
        5071,
        5087
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Virtual networks",
      "pos": [
        5090,
        5106
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Subnets",
      "pos": [
        5109,
        5116
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Availability sets",
      "pos": [
        5119,
        5136
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Resource groups",
      "pos": [
        5139,
        5154
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cloud services",
      "pos": [
        5157,
        5171
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Virtual machines",
      "pos": [
        5174,
        5190
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Endpoints",
      "pos": [
        5193,
        5202
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Network security groups",
      "pos": [
        5205,
        5228
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Roles",
      "pos": [
        5231,
        5236
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To ensure that the name provides enough information to determine to which resource it refers, you should use descriptive names.",
      "pos": [
        5238,
        5365
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Computer names",
      "pos": [
        5371,
        5385
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When administrators create a virtual machine, Microsoft Azure requires them to provide a virtual machine name of up to 15 characters.",
      "pos": [
        5387,
        5520
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure uses the virtual machine name as the Azure virtual machine resource name.",
      "pos": [
        5521,
        5600
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure uses the same name as the computer name for the operating system installed in the virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        5601,
        5705
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, these names might not always be the same.",
      "pos": [
        5706,
        5756
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In case a virtual machine is created from a .vhd image file that already contains an operating system, the virtual machine name in Azure can differ from the virtual machine’s operating system computer name.",
      "pos": [
        5758,
        5964
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This situation can add a degree of difficulty to virtual machine management, which we therefore do not recommend.",
      "pos": [
        5965,
        6078
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Assign the Azure virtual machine resource the same name as the computer name that you assign to the operating system of that virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        6079,
        6220
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We recommend that the Azure virtual machine name be the same as the underlying operating system computer name.",
      "pos": [
        6222,
        6332
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because of this, follow the NetBIOS naming rules as described in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft NetBIOS computer naming conventions<ept id=\"p1\">](https://support.microsoft.com/kb/188997/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        6333,
        6488
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage account names",
      "pos": [
        6494,
        6515
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage accounts have special rules governing their names.",
      "pos": [
        6517,
        6575
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can only use lowercase letters and numbers.",
      "pos": [
        6576,
        6623
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Create a storage account<ept id=\"p1\">](../storage/storage-create-storage-account.md#create-a-storage-account)</ept> for more information.",
      "pos": [
        6624,
        6747
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Additionally, the storage account name, in combination with core.windows.net, should be a globally valid, unique DNS name.",
      "pos": [
        6748,
        6870
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For instance, if the storage account is called mystorageaccount, the following resulting DNS names should be unique:",
      "pos": [
        6871,
        6987
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "mystorageaccount.blob.core.windows.net",
      "pos": [
        6991,
        7029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "mystorageaccount.table.core.windows.net",
      "pos": [
        7032,
        7071
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "mystorageaccount.queue.core.windows.net",
      "pos": [
        7074,
        7113
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure building block names",
      "pos": [
        7120,
        7146
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure building blocks are application-level services that Azure offers, typically to those applications taking advantage of PaaS features, although IaaS resources might leverage some, like SQL Database, Traffic Manager, and others.",
      "pos": [
        7148,
        7379
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These services rely on an array of artifacts that are created and registered in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        7381,
        7467
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These also need to be considered in your naming conventions.",
      "pos": [
        7468,
        7528
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Implementation guidelines recap for naming conventions",
      "pos": [
        7534,
        7588
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Decision:",
      "pos": [
        7590,
        7599
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What are your naming conventions for Azure resources?",
      "pos": [
