    {
      "content": "3. Storage",
      "pos": [
        10210,
        10220
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Storage is an integral part of many Azure solutions.",
      "pos": [
        10222,
        10280
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Storage provides services for storing file data, unstructured data, and messages, and it is also part of the infrastructure supporting virtual machines.",
      "pos": [
        10281,
        10439
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are two types of storage accounts available from Azure.",
      "pos": [
        10441,
        10502
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A standard storage account gives you access to blob storage (used for storing Azure virtual machine disks), table storage, queue storage, and file storage.",
      "pos": [
        10503,
        10658
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Premium storage is designed for high-performance applications, such as SQL Servers in an AlwaysOn cluster, and currently supports Azure virtual machine disks only.",
      "pos": [
        10659,
        10822
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storage accounts are bound to scalability targets.",
      "pos": [
        10824,
        10874
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Azure subscription and service limits, quotas, and constraints<ept id=\"p1\">](../azure-subscription-service-limits.md#storage-limits)</ept> to become familiar with current Azure storage limits.",
      "pos": [
        10875,
        11063
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Also see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure storage scalability and performance targets<ept id=\"p1\">](../storage-scalability-targets.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        11064,
        11160
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure creates virtual machines with an operating system disk, a temporary disk, and zero or more optional data disks.",
      "pos": [
        11162,
        11279
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The operating system disk and data disks are Azure page blobs, whereas the temporary disk is stored locally on the node where the machine lives.",
      "pos": [
        11280,
        11424
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This makes the temporary disk unfit for data that must persist during a system recycle, because the machine might silently be migrated from one node to another, losing any data in that disk.",
      "pos": [
        11425,
        11615
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Do not store anything on the temporary drive.",
      "pos": [
        11616,
        11661
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Operating system disks and data disks have a maximum size of 1023 gigabytes (GB) because the maximum size of a blob is 1024 GB and that must contain the metadata (footer) of the VHD file (a GB is 1024<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;sup&gt;</ph>3<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/sup&gt;</ph> bytes).",
      "pos": [
        11663,
        11883
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can implement disk striping in Windows to surpass this limit.",
      "pos": [
        11884,
        11949
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Striped disks",
      "pos": [
        11955,
        11968
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Besides providing the ability to create disks larger than 1023 GB, in many instances, using striping for data disks enhances performance by allowing multiple blobs to back the storage for a single volume.",
      "pos": [
        11969,
        12173
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With striping, the I/O required to write and read data from a single logical disk proceeds in parallel.",
      "pos": [
        12174,
        12277
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure imposes limits on the amount of data disks and bandwidth available, depending on the virtual machine size.",
      "pos": [
        12279,
        12391
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For details, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Sizes for virtual machines<ept id=\"p1\">](virtual-machines-size-specs.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12392,
        12470
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are using disk striping for Azure data disks, consider the following guidelines:",
      "pos": [
        12472,
        12559
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Data disks should always be the maximum size (1023 GB)",
      "pos": [
        12563,
        12617
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Attach the maximum data disks allowed for the virtual machine size",
      "pos": [
        12620,
        12686
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use storage spaces configuration",
      "pos": [
        12689,
        12721
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use storage striping configuration",
      "pos": [
        12724,
        12758
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Avoid using Azure data disk caching options (caching policy = None)",
      "pos": [
        12761,
        12828
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        12830,
        13013
      ],
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Storage spaces - designing for performance<ept id=\"p1\">](http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/15200.storage-spaces-designing-for-performance.aspx)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Multiple storage accounts",
      "pos": [
        13019,
        13044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using multiple storage accounts to back the disks associated with many virtual machines ensures that the aggregated I/O of those disks is well below the scalability targets for each one of those storage accounts.",
      "pos": [
        13046,
